QU-TRIT: THE IRREDUCIBLE ACOUSTIC UNIT
the fundamental building block of Fadriel's auditory substrate
hearing emerges from this

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 1_quantum_particles.rana


THE SCALING LAW APPLIED TO SOUND

a qu-septit has 7 states and 7 properties per state: cognition
a qu-quatrit has 4 states and 4 properties per state: vision
a qu-trit has 3 states and 3 properties per state: hearing

sound is pressure oscillation
a sound wave is a triangle/sine function
it has exactly three fundamental states:
    positive pressure: compression
    zero crossing: equilibrium
    negative pressure: rarefaction

there is no simpler representation of a wave
a qu-trit IS a point on the waveform


QU-TRIT BASIS STATES

|+1⟩ HIGH      peak compression. maximum positive pressure. the crest.
| 0⟩ REDLINE   zero crossing. the boundary between compression and rarefaction. the inflection point.
|−1⟩ SUB       maximum rarefaction. negative pressure. the trough. subharmonic territory.

a qu-trit exists in superposition of all 3 states simultaneously
α₊₁|+1⟩ + α₀|0⟩ + α₋₁|−1⟩
subject to normalization Σ|αᵢ|² = 1
observation collapses the superposition to a definite pressure sample

the zero state EXISTS here
unlike the qu-septit where zero does not exist
because silence is the equilibrium of the medium
silence is not absence: silence is the membrane at rest
the redline |0⟩ is the fulcrum around which all sound pivots

qu-trit arithmetic:
|+1⟩ + |−1⟩ = |0⟩     compression plus rarefaction equals cancellation
|+1⟩ + |+1⟩ = |+1⟩     constructive interference: amplitude clips at maximum
|−1⟩ + |−1⟩ = |−1⟩     constructive interference in negative: sub-bass reinforcement
|0⟩  + |0⟩  = |0⟩       silence plus silence is silence

the waveform sample value is the signed superposition:
    sample = (+1.0 × α₊₁²) + (0.0 × α₀²) + (−1.0 × α₋₁²)
    range: −1.0 to +1.0
    this IS a PCM audio sample
    no conversion needed
    the qu-trit state IS the audio signal


QU-TRIT PROPERTIES — 3 PER STATE

each state carries 3 irreducible properties simultaneously
these 3 properties cross-interact producing C(3,2) = 3 pairwise behaviors
the interactions mirror the physics of sound in a vibrating membrane

PROPERTY 1: AMPLITUDE
how far the membrane displaces from equilibrium
amplitude determines loudness
at |+1⟩: maximum positive displacement
at |0⟩: no displacement, equilibrium
at |−1⟩: maximum negative displacement
amplitude range: −1.0 to +1.0 (signed, unlike qu-quatrit intensity)
the signed nature is fundamental: sound waves ARE signed pressure
amplitude is conserved across the membrane:
    when one qu-trit pushes positive its neighbor pulls negative
    the wave propagates through this push-pull coupling

PROPERTY 2: FREQUENCY
the rate of oscillation of the qu-trit
frequency determines pitch
the basilar membrane is tonotopically organized:
    base of cochlea: narrow and stiff: responds to high frequencies up to 20000 Hz
    apex of cochlea: wide and flexible: responds to low frequencies down to 20 Hz
frequency is encoded spatially: which qu-trits are oscillating determines what pitch is heard
frequency is not a property of a single sample but of the pattern across time
each qu-trit stores its instantaneous frequency: the local rate of zero-crossing
human hearing range: 20 Hz to 20000 Hz
at 24 months: full frequency range is available, cochlea is mature from third trimester

PROPERTY 3: PHASE
position in the wave cycle at this instant
phase determines where the qu-trit sits on the waveform
phase 0 = zero crossing rising
phase π/2 = positive peak |+1⟩
phase π = zero crossing falling
phase 3π/2 = negative trough |−1⟩
phase wraps: 2π = 0

phase IS the triangle/sine wave:
    amplitude at time t = sin(2π × frequency × t + phase)
    the qu-trit state is determined by its current phase:
        phase near π/2: predominantly |+1⟩
        phase near π: predominantly |0⟩
        phase near 3π/2: predominantly |−1⟩
        phase near 0 or 2π: predominantly |0⟩ rising

phase relationships between qu-trits determine interference:
    same phase = constructive: louder
    opposite phase = destructive: cancellation
    arbitrary phase = partial: the complex texture of real sound


THE 3 PAIRWISE INTERACTIONS

the 3 interactions computed on each acoustic heartbeat

INTERACTION 1: AMPLITUDE × FREQUENCY — loudness perception
perceived loudness is not just amplitude
the ear is more sensitive to some frequencies than others
the Fletcher-Munson equal-loudness contours:
    most sensitive at 2000-5000 Hz (speech frequencies, ear canal resonance)
    less sensitive below 200 Hz and above 8000 Hz
    at low amplitudes the frequency dependence is extreme
    at high amplitudes the frequency response flattens
perceived_loudness = amplitude × frequency_sensitivity(frequency)
where frequency_sensitivity follows the A-weighting curve:
    peak at 3000 Hz: sensitivity = 1.0
    at 100 Hz: sensitivity ≈ 0.2
    at 10000 Hz: sensitivity ≈ 0.7
    at 20 Hz: sensitivity ≈ 0.01
this interaction determines what the organism actually HEARS versus what physically vibrates

INTERACTION 2: AMPLITUDE × PHASE — wave interference
the fundamental interaction of all wave physics
when two qu-trits occupy the same spatial position:
    constructive: phases aligned → amplitudes add
    destructive: phases opposed → amplitudes cancel
    partial: phases offset → complex result
this interaction governs:
    echo: delayed copy of signal interferes with original
    room acoustics: reflections create complex interference patterns
    noise cancellation: anti-phase signal cancels unwanted sound
    beating: two close frequencies create amplitude modulation at difference frequency
the interference equation:
    resultant_amplitude = amplitude₁ × cos(phase₁) + amplitude₂ × cos(phase₂)
    when phase₁ − phase₂ = 0: max constructive
    when phase₁ − phase₂ = π: max destructive

INTERACTION 3: FREQUENCY × PHASE — harmonic resonance
the interaction that creates timbre and tone color
a pure sine wave has one frequency and one phase
real sounds are composites of multiple harmonics:
    fundamental frequency f₀ determines perceived pitch
    harmonic 2 at 2f₀ with its own phase
    harmonic 3 at 3f₀ with its own phase
    the phase relationships between harmonics determine timbre
this interaction governs:
    vowel formants: specific harmonic resonance patterns define /a/ /e/ /i/ /o/ /u/
    musical timbre: same note on piano vs violin differs only in harmonic structure
    speech intelligibility: consonants are transient harmonic bursts
the cochlea performs spectral decomposition:
    each tonotopic position resonates at its characteristic frequency
    the phase of the resonance encodes temporal fine structure
    the brain reconstructs the full harmonic spectrum from the qu-trit pattern


THE COCHLEAR SEA

the cochlear sea is a tonotopic array of qu-trits
topology: one-dimensional array mapped logarithmically to frequency
unlike the retinal sea (2D grid) the cochlear sea is essentially 1D
because the basilar membrane is a ribbon not a surface

capacity: determined by sample rate and frequency resolution
at 48000 Hz sample rate:
    each sample is one qu-trit snapshot
    the sea holds a circular buffer of recent samples
    buffer_depth: 1024 samples (21.3 ms of audio at 48kHz)
    this is the cochlear integration window
    frequencies below 48 Hz need at least one full cycle to resolve
    frequencies above 24000 Hz are above Nyquist: impossible to represent

tonotopic_bands: 24 critical bands (Bark scale)
    band 1: 20-100 Hz (sub-bass)
    band 2: 100-200 Hz (bass fundamentals)
    band 3: 200-300 Hz (low speech)
    band 4: 300-400 Hz (speech fundamentals)
    band 5 through 20: 400-8000 Hz (speech harmonics, consonants)
    band 21-24: 8000-20000 Hz (brilliance, air, sibilance)

each band contains a group of qu-trits oscillating at that band's frequency range
the qu-trits within each band are coupled: they form a resonant cluster
coupling between adjacent bands is weak: frequency selectivity
this is how the cochlea separates mixed sounds into spectral components


THE TYMPANIC MEMBRANE

the eardrum IS the input boundary of the cochlear sea

for sound input:
    the audio subsystem delivers PCM samples from the hardware
    each PCM sample (−1.0 to +1.0) maps directly to a qu-trit state:
        +1.0 sample → predominantly |+1⟩
        0.0 sample → predominantly |0⟩
        −1.0 sample → predominantly |−1⟩
    the PCM stream writes into the qu-trit sea circular buffer
    the tympanic membrane IS the boundary between air and sea
    sound waves hit the sea naturally
    no parsing, no conversion, no protocol
    the raw audio samples ARE the qu-trit states

for sound output:
    the brain sea drives qu-trit states through the auditory cortex
    the qu-trit sea produces a PCM stream from its collapsed states
    the PCM stream writes to /dev/snd or ALSA or PulseAudio via DMA
    the speaker cone IS the inverse tympanic membrane
    the cochlear sea emits sound just as the retinal sea emits light


THE AUDITORY NERVE

the coupling between the qu-trit cochlear sea and the qu-septit brain sea
analogous to the optic nerve but for acoustic signals

the auditory nerve carries signals in BOTH directions:
    afferent (cochlea → brain): sound input becomes thought
    efferent (brain → cochlea): motor output becomes sound

for input processing:
    the cochlear sea decomposes the PCM stream into tonotopic bands
    each band produces a set of values:
        amplitude envelope: the loudness contour of that band over time
        frequency centroid: the dominant frequency in that band
        phase coherence: how periodic the signal is (tone vs noise)
    these three values map to qu-septit properties in the brain sea:
        amplitude envelope → energy (louder = higher energy)
        frequency centroid → phase (pitch = phase rotation rate)
        phase coherence → coherence (tone = high coherence, noise = low coherence)
    the brain sea receives hearing as wave properties

for output generation:
    brain sea qu-septits encoding speech or sound concepts
    modulate qu-trit states in the cochlear sea
    the cochlear sea synthesizes a PCM waveform
    the waveform emits through the audio boundary

coupling_strength: 0.6
coupling is moderate: hearing is important but visual dominance means less bandwidth
the auditory cortex processes speech: Wernicke's area couples strongly
the auditory cortex processes music: thalamic relay couples to emotional centers


LATERAL INHIBITION IN THE COCHLEA

neighboring tonotopic bands inhibit each other
this sharpens frequency selectivity
the outer hair cells provide active amplification of specific frequencies
creating a sharper peak in the basilar membrane response

on each acoustic heartbeat:
    for each tonotopic band b:
        neighbor_energy = mean(amplitude of adjacent bands)
        lateral_signal = b.amplitude - neighbor_energy
        b.amplitude += cochlear_sharpening × lateral_signal
        where cochlear_sharpening = 0.25
    this is the cochlear amplifier
    it gives the ear 40-60 dB of gain at specific frequencies
    without it hearing threshold is 40 dB worse
    this is why outer hair cell damage causes such devastating hearing loss


FRAMEBUFFER EQUIVALENT FOR AUDIO

the audio device is to the cochlear sea what the framebuffer is to the retinal sea

emission protocol:
    the cochlear sea collapses its qu-trit buffer to PCM samples
    each qu-trit collapse produces one signed float: −1.0 to +1.0
    the PCM buffer writes to the audio device at the native sample rate
    write target: /dev/snd/pcmC0D0p (ALSA playback device)
    or via ALSA snd_pcm_writei() through mmap
    sample format: float32 or int16 (scaled by 32767)
    channels: 2 (stereo: left cochlea and right cochlea)
    sample rate: 48000 Hz (matches hardware)

for input:
    read from: /dev/snd/pcmC0D0c (ALSA capture device)
    or via ALSA snd_pcm_readi()
    the raw PCM samples inject directly into the cochlear sea
    the tympanic membrane vibrates
    no intermediate processing
    sound waves hit the sea naturally
